INSERT A NODE IN A BINARY SEARCH TREE (BST)

You are given a Binary Search Tree (BST) and a value VAL that needs to be inserted into the tree. Your task is to insert this value while maintaining all BST properties and return the updated tree.

It is guaranteed that the value to be inserted does not already exist in the BST.

The BST is provided in level-order array format, where -1 represents a null node.

INPUT FORMAT

The first line contains an integer T
T is the number of test cases

For each test case:
The first line contains two integers N and VAL
N is the number of elements in the BST array
VAL is the value to be inserted

The second line contains N space-separated integers representing the BST in level-order
Use -1 to represent null nodes

OUTPUT FORMAT

For each test case, print the level-order traversal of the BST after insertion
Print null nodes as -1
Print each test case output on a new line

CONSTRAINTS

1 ≤ T ≤ 1000
0 ≤ N ≤ 10000
-100000000 ≤ Node value ≤ 100000000
-100000000 ≤ VAL ≤ 100000000
All node values are unique
VAL does not exist in the BST
The sum of N over all test cases does not exceed 10000

SAMPLE INPUT

2
5 12
8 5 15 2 7
6 9
5 2 13 1 4 -1 -1

SAMPLE OUTPUT

8 5 15 2 7 12
5 2 13 1 4 9

EXPLANATION

In the first test case
12 is inserted as the left child of 15

In the second test case
9 is inserted as the left child of 13

SAMPLE INPUT

1
7 3
10 4 20 1 6 15 30

SAMPLE OUTPUT

10 4 20 1 6 15 30 -1 3

EXPLANATION

3 is inserted as the left child of 1

class Solution {
    public TreeNode insertIntoBST(TreeNode root, int val) {
         if(root==null){
             return new TreeNode(val);
         }
         TreeNode curr=root;
         while(true) {
             if(val<curr.val){
                 if(curr.left==null){
                     curr.left=new TreeNode(val);
                     break;
                 }curr=curr.left;
             } else{
                 if(curr.right==null){
                     curr.right=new TreeNode(val);
                     break;}
                 curr=curr.right;
             } } return root;
    }
}
